\begin{align*}
\left|A-(1,0,z)\right| &= \left|B-(1,0,z)\right| &&\text{so from the symmetry of the problem, i.e. $A$ and $C$ are symmetric across the $yz$-plane, we have that $z=\frac{2-\sqrt{3}+1}{2}.$  Note that if $2-\sqrt{3} < 0,$ this is a contradiction, since points generally cannot denote imaginary quantities.}\\
\therefore\,z&=\frac{3-\sqrt{3}}{2}. \end{align*}
Thus, the desired point is the point $\boxed{\left(1,0,\frac{3-\sqrt{3}}{2}\right).}$
